column56:
I think that dedicated recycling programs where there are financial incentives to the hospital are the only thing that would work in our setting.  
my concern about changing practice is that there are so many factors involved in good patient outcome, that doing anything that is perceived as potentially inferior will not be supported.
However, if we can take all the paper/packaging/plastic etc and recycle it, that would not require a significant change in our practice.

column56: I'm quite willing to switch from disposable instruments to reusable items as long as the quality and safety is similar.  Also, it's not clear that the environmental impact of reusable items is less given the water and time and materials to clean them, I would like to have data concerning this to better inform my practice.  Additionally, as my operations are often time critical (ie major trauma), these would be more difficult to individually transition as in those cases I just need things fast.

column56: i think that one of the biggest incentives is to have the administration on board - so there has to be a financial benefit for the hospital.  there are so many hidden costs in using reusable equipment (reusable trocars for example) that we stopped doing it b/c it was actually costing us more in time/people.  Reusable energy equipment (harmonic) is easy b/c it costs less and it's easy for administration to support it.  anything that adds work for the staff will not work given staff shortage. in our area most hospitals are in perpetual crisis mode.

column56: I don’t need perks though that would be nice. I am extremely motivated because I want a better future for my son and frankly I feel like a hypocrite standing at scrub sink with water running when it doesn’t need to continuously or changing out/throwing away scrub hats… I’m not advocating reusing gloves and understand there is a balance but we simply have not paid much attention in this area and the companies and hospitals have far too much incentives for disposable items or not allowing to use what you need (eg only a fraction of a silastic patch but then throwing away the remaining large portion and not allowing resterilization without consideration of how the patch is being used). Regulatory bodies need to help out too- right now that is not part of FDA or CMS DNA.

column56:
waste of single-use items is a huge problem, most of the waste does nothing to improve patient outcomes. the first step to change this will likely involve collecting data on the quantity of waste and publicising it at surgical meetings and at meetings of hospital administrators. 
A huge efort is needed to educate hospital staff about the magnitude of waste, and the definition of waste..... ie utilization of resources that does not improve patient outcomes.  only then can the problem begin to be addressed, and attitudes among medical personnel and hospital regulators change in a postive direction.
